>[!quote]
>s: To make the most of this book, take the time to experiment between each chapter, be it on your own project or by exploring the notebooks we provide. Then try rewriting those notebooks from scratch on a new dataset. It's only by practicing (and failing) a lot that you will get an intuition of how to train a model.

>[!tip]
>Most important for a project DL is data availability.
>Don't waste months or years while they attempt to find their perfect dataset.

In organizational context, showing the idea that can really work - a prototype.

Not good at recognizing images that are significantly different in structure or style to those used to train the model.

=> For instance, if there were no black-and-white images in the training data, the model may do poorly on black-and-white images.

# State of DL by the start of 2020.

## Computer Vision.

Computers can recognize what items are in the image - *Object Recognition*.

Recognizing where objects in image are, highlighting their location, naming each found object - *Object Detection*.

Where every pixel is categorized based on what kind of object it is part ofthis is called*segmentation*.
